<H3> <TI>   New Party Advocates Moravian Autonomy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Party Advocates Moravian Autonomy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1906115594 Prague CTK in English 1909 GMT 18 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1906115594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brno, South Moravia, June 18 (CTK) -- A new Moravian 
party, the Movement for Self-Governing Moravia and Silesia 
(HSMS), was established today electing Jan Smejkal its chairman. 
Smejkal told CTK that the priority goal of the HSMS, registered 
on June 1, was self-rule for Moravia. 
  He said that the participants in the constituent congress 
considered the movement a successor organisation to the original 
Self-Governing Democracy Movement for Moravia and Silesia 
(HSDMS) which was transformed into the present Bohemian and 
Moravian Centre Party (CMSS) in January. Some members of the 
original movement, especially those active at Brno's local 
administration, disagreed with the move. 
  Delegates from the Brno organisaton accused CMSS Chairman 
Jan 
Krycer at the CMSS congress on June 4 "of a loss of prestige of 
the party, disintegration of the organisational structure and 
decline in the party's popularity." The CMSS has 9 out of a 
total of 200 parliamentary seats. But according to the latest 
public opinion polls, it would not cross the parliamentary 
border of 5 per cent now. 

</TEXT>

