<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   SDRP Leader on Church's `Defeat' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SDRP Leader on Church's `Defeat' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2006200694 Warsaw PAP in English 1918 GMT 20 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2006200694 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lodz, June 20--The low turnout in Sunday's local 
government elections is a defeat of all political forces in 
Poland, but the greatest defeat was suffered by the church, 
according to deputy head of the Social Democracy of the Republic 
of Poland (SDRP) Leszek Miller. 
  "The church has mobilized all its strength, this time it put 
everything in the balance, (...) but it failed to mobilize such 
masses of voters to go to the ballot box it counted on. I 
believe this is the expression of disagreement of many believers 
to a politicized role the church has recently sought to play in 
Poland," Miller told journalists in Lodz on Monday. 
  Miller thought that the outcome of the elections offers a 
chance for political stability in Poland. It will be possible 
to keep the election and political timetables--presidential 
elections in over a year, next local government elections in 
four years, and parliamentary elections in less than four years. 
He added that the elections must have convinced all politicians 
and all Poles that the "road to a civic society will be arduous, 
difficult and long." 

</TEXT>

