<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moravcik: Old Clearing Account To Be Abolished </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moravcik: Old Clearing Account To Be Abolished </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2106111094 Prague CTK in English 1108 GMT 20 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2106111094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, June 20 (CTK) -- The Czech Republic and 
Slovakia have agreed to abolish the old clearing account, 
containing commercial debts which arose before the currency 
separation in February 1993, and have decided that companies 
themselves will cover exchange rate differences that have since 
arisen. 
  "Companies themselves will decide what exchange rate they 
will use to settle their debts on the account. It is untenable 
that differences from changes in the exchange rates be paid from 
the state budget," Slovak Premier Jozef Moravcik said on his 
return from the economic forum in Crans-Montana, Switzerland, 
where he also met Czech Premier Vaclav Klaus. 
  The possibility of companies paying the differences, on 
which 
both premiers agreed, is only one option. "Companies can agree 
on compensation through supplies of goods, or each paying half 
the difference," Moravcik said. He admitted that Slovak 
companies would be the losers. 
  The account's abolition must be approved by both countries' 
parliaments. Moravcik said it could take effect as of August 1 
if sufficient legislation is found to serve as a basis for the 
step. He admitted that the account might be abolished after the 
autumn Parliament elections in Slovakia, because in contrast to 
the Slovak Parliament, the Czech one will be holding its last 
session in July. 
  Moravcik said that he considered it important that the Czech 
side had promised it would not "begin any initiative" to abolish 
the mutual clearing account from the customs union. That does 
not mean that mutual payment agreements could not be improved if 
either side wants to change something, he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

