<F P=100> ROMANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UVR Seeks Educational Rights for Minorities </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UVR Seeks Educational Rights for Minorities </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2106170694 Bucharest Radio Romania Network in Romanian 
1300 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2106170694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest Radio Romania Network </F>
<F P=105>  Romanian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Vatra Romaneasca Union [UVR] has faxed us a 
message containing a number of stipulations they propose for 
inclusion in the Draft Education Law. 
  Thus, they propose that secondary education in the Romanian 
language should be organized and operate in every village, town, 
and municipality of the country. Entrance examinations, as well 
as all graduation examinations of every kind of educational 
institutions should be held solely in Romanian, while ethnic 
minorities should be granted, in the domain of education, the 
same rights as the Romanian ethnic minority is granted in 
Hungary, and the same rights as ethnic minorities are granted in 
Western democracies, that is, rights as stipulated by the 
relevant international regulations. 
  These proposals were worked out during a meeting of the UVR 
National Steering Committee, which was held on 18 June in the 
town of Lugoj, says the message faxed to us by Zeno Opris, 
chairman of the UVR. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

