<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jovanovic Criticizes UN Policy in Crisis </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jovanovic Criticizes UN Policy in Crisis </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1906174294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1728 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1906174294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Kragujevac, Yugoslavia, June 19 (TANJUG) -- Yugoslav 
Foreign Minister Vladislav Jovanovic said Sunday that U.N. Envoy 
Yasushi Akashi's statement, in which he said that the U.N. would 
pursue a "stick and carrot" policy towards the Federal Republic 
of Yugoslavia, confirmed that some members of the world 
organization were pursuing a partial policy. 
  The countries represented on the Contact Group for 
Bosnia-Herzegovina have a great responsibility not to allow to 
be drawn again into the trap of partiality and belief that they 
could achieve something by pursuing the "stick and carrot" 
policy, Jovanovic said in a radio interview broadcast from 
Kragujevac in central Serbia. 
  Referring to hints that the new maps for 
Bosnia-Herzegovina's 
territorial division would be submitted to the warring sides as 
an ultimatum, Jovanovic said that this was not yet clear and 
that everybody should wait. 
  However, if it would be merely a continuation of the earlier 
policy of favouring the Bosnian Moslems and Croats and punishing 
the Serbs, then it would obviously not lead to any results, 
Jovanovic said. 
  The Contact Group is soon expected to present the maps for 
Bosnia's division, according to which 51 percent of the 
territory of Bosnia-Herzegovina would go to the Moslem-Croat 
federation and 49 percent to the Bosnian Serbs. 

</TEXT>

