<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Steady Rise in Industrial Output Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Steady Rise in Industrial Output Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206110094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1035 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2206110094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, June 22 (TANJUG) -- Yugoslavia's 
industrial production has doubled since an economic economic 
reform programme was launched in late January. Industry, apart 
from the power industry, had a growth index of 205 per cent in 
the January-to-May period. The figures for May, for the first 
time in three months, show a certain drop in the industrial 
production growth -- 6.8 per cent below the figure for April -- 
but still a rise of 3.9 per cent. Central Bank Governor 
Dragoslav Avramovic, architect of the economic recovery and 
monetary reconstruction programme, describes the results as a 
remarkable success. "We may be proud, all the more so because 
this comes after last year's total monetary collapse and in 
conditions of sanctions," says Avramovic. The U.N. Security 
Council clamped strict economic sanctions on Yugoslavia on May 
30, 1992. The industrial output dropped by 20 per cent in 1992 
as against 1991 and by a further 37.3 per cent in 1993. "Credit 
for the revival of production goes primarily to the banks, which 
have been operating and giving loans in the worst of economic 
conditions," says Avramovic. As a result, most banks are 
grappling with the problem of insolvency, and the federal 
government and the Cental Bank will soon be taking steps to 
consolidate the banks' position, he explains. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

