<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Milosevic Condemns `Biased Media Reports' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Milosevic Condemns `Biased Media Reports' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2006181194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1724 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2006181194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, June 20 (TANJUG)--Serbian President 
Slobodan Milosevic, French General Pierre-Marie Gallois and 
Greek poet and journalist Dimitris Analis condemned here Monday 
the biased media reports on the causes and protagonists of the 
crisis in former Yugoslavia. 
  The media war, which is undoubtedly being waged against our 
country, had helped dismember former Yugoslavia, Milosevic said 
during a talk with Gallois and Analis, who also comes from 
France where he currently lives, the presidential office said in 
a statement. 
  Milosevic and his guests, who are on a several-day visit to 
Yugoslavia at the invitation of the Yugoslav Government, agreed 
that it was a primary moral duty of all conscientious 
intellectuals to stand up against such manipulation with public 
opinion. 
  Gallois expressed to President Milosevic his support for the 
efforts Serbia and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia are making 
to secure a stable peace in the territory of former Yugoslavia. 
  The French general, a prominent fighter against fascism in 
the Second World War and former chief of the French General 
Staff, also expressed his strong disagreement with the policy of 
pressures and sanctions of the international community against 
the Serbian people. 
  The resoluteness of Serbia and its citizens to persist in 
protecting their legitimate interests set an example to the 
countries which strive to equality-based relations among states 
and peoples and which are determined to defend their freedom and 
independence, the guests from France said. 
  The statement said Gallois and Analis had promised Milosevic 
to continue to openly urge the affirmation of truth on the 
crisis in former Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

