<F P=101> Romania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Iliescu, Havel Sign Czech-Romanian Treaty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Iliescu, Havel Sign Czech-Romanian Treaty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2206131594 Prague CTK in English 1235 GMT 22 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2206131594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest, June 22 (CTK) -- The Czech and Romanian 
presidents, Vaclav Havel and Ion Iliescu, signed today a treaty 
of friendship and cooperation between their countries. 
  At a following press conference Havel said the agreement was 
culmination of the traditionally good and well developing 
bilateral relations, and at the same time a basis for further 
cooperation to be also supported by an agreement on a free-trade 
zone, which is to be signed by the two countries' premiers in 
autumn. 
  Iliescu pointed to the long and extraordinarily positive 
tradition of Czech-Romanian relations, and to the events of 
1968, when Romania was the only country of the communist East 
Europe to openly oppose the Soviet invasion of Czechoslovakia. 
Iliescu confirmed that the Czech-Romanian relations would 
mainly include economic cooperation. 
  Havel said he had invited Iliescu to visit the Czech 
Republic. 
  Asked whether or not Romania was interested in joining the 
Visegrad group (the Czech Republic, Hungary, Poland and 
Slovakia), Iliescu said that it was rather interested in getting 
closer to the Central European Initiative (the above four 
countries, and Austria, Italy, Bosnia-Herzegovina, Croatia, 
Macedonia [The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM] 
and Slovenia). 
  Later today Havel is to meet with Czechs living in Romania 
and Czech diplomatic staff in Bucharest. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

