<H3> <TI>   Cabinet Rejects Bill on Administrative Units </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cabinet Rejects Bill on Administrative Units </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2206184994 Prague CTK in English 1619 GMT 22 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2206184994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, June 22 (CTK) -- At its session today the 
cabinet did not approve a constitutional bill on higher 
self-governing units which has been submitted by Deputy Premier 
Jan Kalvoda, Deputy Premier Ivan Kocarnik told reporters today. 
  However, the cabinet must submit the bill to parliament by 
June 30, Kocarnik added. 
  He said the government had thoroughly discussed the document 
which anticipated the creation of 13 units which would include 
units formed on the basis of administrative centers of the 
former regions (Brno is a chief city of the former South 
Moravian region) and new districts of Karlovy Vary, Liberec, 
Pardubice, Jihlava, Olomouc and Zlin. 
  According to the bill, Prague and Central Bohemia would form 
one unit. 
  There were initially seven regions (five Czech and two 
Moravian) - Central Bohemia with Prague as a chief city, South 
Bohemia - Pardubice, West Bohemia - Plzen, North Bohemia - Usti 
nad Labem, East Bohemia - Hradec Kralove, South Moravia - Brno 
and North Moravia - Ostrava. The city of Prague was also a 
region. These regions were abolished in 1991, and 72 districts 
came into existence instead. 

</TEXT>

