<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ethnic Hungarian Parties Consider Coalition </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ethnic Hungarian Parties Consider Coalition </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2106185194 Prague CTK in English 1557 GMT 21 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2106185194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, June 21 (CTK) -- Although it is still 
not known how the Hungarian minority parties will go into 
Slovakia's autumn elections, their most likely strategy is a 
coalition -- either between Egyutteles [Coexistence] and the 
Hungarian Christian Democratic Movement (MKDH) on their own or 
with the addition of the Hungarian Civic Party (MOS). 
  Egyutteles and the MKDH are both in the five-party coalition 
government of Jozef Moravcik, while the MOS is a minor non- 
parliamentary party. 
  The prospect of coupling with a third Hungarian party has 
become something of an apple of discord between Egyutteles and 
the MKDH. Initially Egyutteles propounded a coalition embracing 
all four Hungarian parties in Slovakia, which the MKDH opposed. 
Egyutteles now does not directly reject the idea of a three-way 
coalition but it is seeking reassurances from the MOS that after 
election MOS deputies will not desert the Hungarian bloc for 
some right-of-center Slovak party. 
  The situation is further complicated by personal antipathy 
between Egyutteles Chairman Miklos Duray and MOS Chairman Laszlo 
Nagy, who in the past has criticized the former for nationalism. 
  The MKDH backs MOS admission to the loose coalition 
currently 
existing with Egyutteles so that, in the words of MKDH chairman 
Vojtech Bugar, "not one Hungarian vote is lost" 
  Egyutteles deputy Edita Bauerova said at a party press 
conference today that the MKDH had, however, not yet stated its 
conditions for any such coalition. 
  A two- or three-party coalition will not affect requirements 
for entry to parliament. For both, a minimum of seven per cent 
of the vote is needed. Observers agree a four-party Hungarian 
coalition is probably out of the question because it would 
require ten percent of the vote. The Hungarian minority in 
Slovakia (i.e. the voting base for the Hungarian bloc) numbers 
some 560,000 people, 10.8 percent of the total population. 
  Egyutteles is also toying with the idea of including 
candidates from the fourth minority party, the Hungarian 
People's Party (MLS, also non-parliamentary) on its election 
lists, as the law allows, but the MKDH does not hide its 
objections to this strategy. 
  Whatever the outcome of these pre-electoral maneuvers, 
observers believe Egyutteles and the MKDH will retain their 
ability to tip the scales in favor of the anti-Meciar government. 
  General elections will be held in Slovakia on September 30 
and October 1. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-32376 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu121__a94031" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-121-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   NDS, DU Consider Merger After Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NDS, DU Consider Merger After Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2206132194 Prague CTK in English 1231 GMT 22 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2206132194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, June 22 (CTK) -- The National 
Democratic Party (NDS) and the Democratic Union of Slovakia (DU) 
may merge after the autumn parliamentary elections, NDS Chairman 
Ludovit Cernak told journalists today. 
  The June polls gave three percent to the NDS (5 deputies in 
the 150-seat Slovak parliament) and six percent to Premier Jozef 
Moravcik's DU (14 deputies). 
  Two weeks ago Moravcik offered the NDS to run on the DU 
slate 
and to get three seats in parliament provided the parties 
succeed in the elections, Cernak said. 
  On Saturday [18 June] the NDS central council approved a 
decision of its executive committee to join the DU list of 
candidates. This is the best way for the party how to "appeal 
to non-left-orientated and non-Meciarite" voters, Cernak said. 
  The decision is subject to approval by the DU national 
council which will take place on Saturday. Although it had 
opted for a separate candidature in the elections, it is likely 
to change the tack. 
  Two weeks ago Cernak said that the "NDS is almost certain to 
run the elections on the KDH (Christian Democratic Movement) 
list." At present, the offers from the DU and KDH are "of about 
the same quality," Cernak stated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

