<H3> <TI>   Cabinet Approves 1995 Budget Proposal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cabinet Approves 1995 Budget Proposal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2206082794 Prague CTK in English 0604 GMT 22 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2206082794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava June 22 (CTK) -- Slovakia plans its 1995 
budget to have a deficit of 12 billion Slovak crowns, making up 
three percent of GDP, Finance Minister Rudolf Filkus said after 
a cabinet session last night. 
  The cabinet approved a budget proposal for 1995, planning a 
15- percent unemployment rate, a two percent GDP growth and an 
eight percent inflation rate. 
  The cabinet asked the Finance Ministry to discuss the budget 
proposal with representatives of the central bank and of the 
National Property Fund (FNM). 
  Filkus said a problem was the amount of debt to be paid next 
year. Slovakia is expected to pay 38 to 44 billion Slovak 
crowns (about $1.3 billion), an increase by 11 to 17 billion 
crowns compared with this year. This increase is higher than 
the year-on-year growth in budget revenues and would draw a 
quarter of annual budget expenditures. 
  In case the central bank and the FNM refuse to share in 
paying back the debt, the budget deficit could not be 
maintained, Filkus added. 
  In an interview published by yesterday's issue of the 
economic daily HOSPODARSKE NOVINY, Premier Jozef Moravcik said 
Slovakia's goal for this year was to completely halt the fall of 
GDP, reduce the inflation rate to 13 percent (from last year's 
23.1 percent) and maintain the budget deficit at 14 billion 
crowns. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
