<H3> <TI>   Goncz Views `Useful' Visit to United States </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Goncz Views `Useful' Visit to United States </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2406080294 Budapest MTI in English 1840 GMT 23 Jun 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2406080294 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 23 Jun (MTI) -- "The visit achieved our 
goals, this is as much as could be desired," Hungarian President 
Arpad Goncz said on Thursday, summing up the results of his 
three-day unofficial visit to the United States with Slovak 
President Michal Kovac. 
  The Hungarian president said the entire visit was 
characterized by a pleasant atmosphere, and can unequivocally be 
termed as useful for both Hungary and Slovakia. 
  The two presidents received honours from the New York-based 
Institute for East-West Studies, in recognition of their 
activity for international reconciliation. 
  "Thanks to splendid organization by the host institute, we 
had an opportunity both in Washington and in New York to meet 
with the political elite that shapes public opinion and 
participates in decision-making," Goncz said. 
  "The discussions created an opportunity for me to set forth 
issues through which I was able to clarify the recurring 
misunderstandings, including the one whereby Hungary, through 
its minority policy, is a trouble-maker and danger factor in 
Central Europe," the President said. 
  U.S. President Bill Clinton received the Hungarian and 
Slovak 
Presidents at the White House. 
  On Thursday, Goncz and Kovac held a lecture in the morning, 
and attended an informal discussion at the Foreign Relations 
Council. The topics of the meeting were the more general Central 
European issues. 
  The Hungarian president will conclude his vist to the United 
States and leave New York for Budapest on Thursday evening. 

</TEXT>

