<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Call for `Historical Compromise' With Hungary </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Call for `Historical Compromise' With Hungary </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2306135994 Prague CTK in English 0807 GMT 22 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2306135994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Bratislava, June 22 (CTK) -- [passage omitted] 
  The prize of the Institute for East-West Studies (IEWS) 
jointly awarded to the Slovak and Hungarian presidents, Michal 
Kovac and Arpad Goncz, is, in fact, an open call for the two 
countries' responsible politicians to start dealing at last with 
the idea of a historical compromise, the independent NARODNA 
OBRODA says. 
  "Kovac and Goncz are actually only symbolic proponents and 
creators of this objectively inevitable process although symbols 
are irreplaceable and very necessary," the daily notes. 
  Realistic people on both banks of the Danube River are fully 
aware that what had happened between French and Germans or 
Austrians and Italians must happen between Slovaks and 
Hungarians as well, the paper states. 
  Afterwards, the Slovak-Hungarian compromise could serve as a 
model for the rest of the postcommunist world, including 
Hungary's other neighbors. "It is in Slovaks' and Hungarians' 
own interest not to postpone the process," the daily adds. 
  "The framework has been created, there is willingness and 
courage. If the process is halted, or something worse occurs, 
the present and future generations could curse their fathers and 
grand- fathers for not having used the offered historical 
chance. And it is here, indeed," the paper concludes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

