<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   GDP Decline Said Halted in 1993 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    GDP Decline Said Halted in 1993 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94CH0280B Prague HOSPODARSKE NOVINY in Czech 25 Apr 94 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> 94CH0280B </F>
<F P=104>  Prague HOSPODARSKE NOVINY </F>
<F P=105>  Czech </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by vac: "Last Year, the Decline in the Gross </F>
Domestic Product Was Halted"] 
  [Text] According to the expectations and estimates of the 
most important economists, including even members of the 
Economic Council of Ministers, the decline in the gross domestic 
product [GDP] stopped in 1993. When compared with 1992, it 
reached the level of 99.7 percent--that is to say, it was 0.3 
percent lower. HOSPODARSKE NOVINY has already reported on these 
fundamental preliminary data issued by the Czech Statistical 
Office. In more detailed materials, the Czech Statistical Office 
notes that the figures for 1992 and 1993 have been rendered 
extensively more accurate. According to these materials, the GDP 
for 1993 attained a value of 923.1 billion korunas [Kc]--that 
is, approximately Kc89,400 per capita. Other facts that were 
reported regarding these computations by the statistical 
authorities are also of interest. The implicit deflator (the 
cumulative price index) of the GDP attained a level of 115.3 
points. For purposes of comparison, it is possible to state that 
the measure of inflation, computed on the basis of the consumer 
price index (a sliding average for 12 months compared with the 
same period a year ago), reached a 1993 level of 120.8 percent. 
  From the standpoint of aggregate demand, the slight decline 
in the GDP was brought about by the gross creation of fixed 
capital (by declining by 7.9 percent), whereas all other 
components increased: Consumption by households increased by 1.5 
percent and consumption by the government by 1.1 percent, and 
the asset portion of the foreign trade balance rose 44 percent. 
A decline in inventories and reserves (approximately 6 percent 
of the total volume of the GDP) in 1993 was approximately equal 
to the level of 1992. 
  There was a more express rise in some expenditure components 
of the GDP (computed in current prices). The share of household 
consumption rose from 51.5 percent in 1992 to 54.2 percent in 
1993, government consumption increased from 23.1 percent to 25.7 
percent, and the positive balance of foreign trade rose from 1.2 
percent to 3.1 percent. On the other hand, there was a decline 
in the share accounted for by gross capital formation from 24.7 
percent to 23.3 percent. There was a specific increase in the 
share of inventory and reserve decline, which dropped from 
- 0.7 percent to - 6.3 percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-32427 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu122_c_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-122 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  30 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

