<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Retake Territory in Separation Zone </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs Retake Territory in Separation Zone </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206180594 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1715 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2206180594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Knin, 22 Jun (TANJUG) -- Members of the Serbian army 
of Krajina returned to positions in the area of the village of 
Kakma near Benkovac, along the Croatian-Krajina separation line, 
an area that has been designated by the Zagreb agreement as 
being within the zone of separation. 
  This was also confirmed by Lieutenant Colonel Marinko Gajic, 
deputy commander of the Serbian army of Krajina, who explained 
the move as a measure of caution against increased Croatian 
threats to the effect that they would forcibly capture the water 
springs in this village. The source supplying Benkovac with 
water has been controlled by the Serbian army of Krajina until 
recently, but became part of the so-called zone of separation in 
accordance with the Zagreb agreement. This area is now under 
the jurisdiction of UNPROFOR's [UN Protection Force] Canadian 
battalion. Allan Roberts, spokesman for Sector South, told 
TANJUG's correspondent that the situation is being assessed 
"very carefully," and that consultations are being conducted at 
the moment, "so nothing specific can be said." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

